  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the procedure to apply to an RTI?",
  "response": "The Right to Information (RTI) Act, 2005, is an Act of the Parliament of India that sets out the rules and procedures regarding citizens' right to information. Here\u2019s a general procedure to apply for an RTI:\n\n1. **Identify the Department**: Determine which public authority holds the information you seek. It's crucial to direct your request to the correct department.\n\n2. **Write the Application**: Draft your RTI application. You can write it on a plain paper or use a format specified by the concerned authority if applicable. The application should be addressed to the Public Information Officer (PIO) of the department. Include the following details:\n   - Your full name and contact details (address, phone number, email if available).\n   - A clear and specific description of the information you seek. Avoid vague terms.\n   - Mention the period for which the information is requested, if applicable.\n   - Specify if you need the information in a particular format (print, electronic, etc.).\n\n3. **Language**: The application can be submitted in English, Hindi, or the official language of the area.\n\n4. **Fee Payment**: The application fee is typically Rs. 10. Payment methods vary by department and may include:\n   - Cash\n   - Demand Draft\n   - Banker\u2019s Cheque\n   - Indian Postal Order (IPO)\n\n   Some specific sectors like BPL (Below Poverty Line) applicants might be exempted from the fee, but you will need to provide a proof of the BPL status.\n\n5. **Submit the Application**: You can submit the application by hand, by post, or online if the concerned department provides such a facility. Always keep a copy of the application for your records.\n\n6. **Acknowledgment**: On submission, you should receive an acknowledgment or receipt. If mailing, consider using Registered Post to have a proof of sending.\n\n7. **Timeframe**: The PIO is required to provide the information within 30 days of receipt of the request. If the information concerns the life or liberty of a person, it should be provided within 48 hours.\n\n8. **Appeal Process**: If you do not receive a response or are dissatisfied with the response, you can file an appeal. The first appeal can be filed with the designated Appellate Authority within the public authority. If still unsatisfied, a second appeal can be made to the Central Information Commission or State Information Commission.\n\nAlways check the specific rules and guidelines from the relevant public authority as procedures may slightly differ based on the state or department.",
